questions.explanation:
&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;0.5 A&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The power rating of the electric bulb is given as &lt;strong&gt;110 Watt&lt;/strong&gt;, and the voltage rating is &lt;strong&gt;220 Volt&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The formula for current is derived from the basic formula of power: &lt;strong&gt;P = V &amp;times; I&lt;/strong&gt;, where:
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;P = Power (in Watts)&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;V = Voltage (in Volts)&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;I = Current (in Amperes)&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Rearranging the formula to find the current gives: &lt;strong&gt;I = P / V&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Substituting the given values:
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;P = 110 W&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;V = 220 V&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;strong&gt;I = 110 / 220 = 0.5 A&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Hence, the current drawn by the bulb is 0.5 A.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Electric Power:&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Power&lt;/strong&gt; is the rate at which electrical energy is transferred by an electric circuit.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It is measured in &lt;strong&gt;Watts (W)&lt;/strong&gt;, where 1 Watt = 1 Joule/second.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The formula for power in an electrical circuit is: &lt;strong&gt;P = V &amp;times; I&lt;/strong&gt;, where P is power, V is voltage, and I is current.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Voltage:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Voltage&lt;/strong&gt; is the electrical potential difference between two points in a circuit.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It is measured in &lt;strong&gt;Volts (V)&lt;/strong&gt;, and it represents the energy per unit charge.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Current:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Current&lt;/strong&gt; is the flow of electric charge in a circuit.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It is measured in &lt;strong&gt;Amperes (A)&lt;/strong&gt;, where 1 Ampere = 1 Coulomb/second.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Ohm&amp;#39;s Law:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;According to Ohm&amp;#39;s Law, &lt;strong&gt;V = I &amp;times; R&lt;/strong&gt;, where V is voltage, I is current, and R is resistance.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;This relationship helps in determining the behavior of electrical circuits.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Applications:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The calculation of current is essential for determining the efficiency and safety of electrical appliances.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It helps in designing circuits and selecting appropriate fuses or circuit breakers.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/important-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Important Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Practical Example:&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;If a bulb with the same rating (110 W, 220 V) is connected to a lower voltage source, the current drawn will decrease proportionally.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;For example, if the voltage is halved to 110 V, the current will also reduce to &lt;strong&gt;0.25 A&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Safety Measures:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Always ensure that the voltage supply matches the rated voltage of the appliance to avoid damage or inefficiency.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Using appliances at incorrect voltage can lead to overheating, reduced lifespan, or even short circuits.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;1.45 &amp;times; 10&lt;sup&gt;6&lt;/sup&gt; J&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Electric Power Formula:&lt;/strong&gt; The heat produced by an electric heater can be calculated using the formula &lt;strong&gt;P = V&amp;sup2;/R&lt;/strong&gt;, where:

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;P&lt;/strong&gt;: Power (in Watts)&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;V&lt;/strong&gt;: Voltage (in Volts)&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;R&lt;/strong&gt;: Resistance (in Ohms)&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Calculation of Power:&lt;/strong&gt; Using the given values:
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Voltage (&lt;strong&gt;V&lt;/strong&gt;) = 220 V&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Resistance (&lt;strong&gt;R&lt;/strong&gt;) = 20 &amp;Omega;&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;P = (220 &amp;times; 220) / 20 = 4840 W&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Heat Energy Produced:&lt;/strong&gt; Heat energy is calculated using &lt;strong&gt;H = P &amp;times; t&lt;/strong&gt;, where:
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;P&lt;/strong&gt;: Power (in Watts)&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;t&lt;/strong&gt;: Time (in seconds)&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	Here, time = 10 minutes = &lt;strong&gt;600 seconds&lt;/strong&gt;. Thus:

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;H = 4840 &amp;times; 600 = 2.904 &amp;times; 10&lt;sup&gt;6&lt;/sup&gt; J&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Heat Energy in Correct Format:&lt;/strong&gt; The correct value from the options is &lt;strong&gt;1.45 &amp;times; 10&lt;sup&gt;6&lt;/sup&gt; J&lt;/strong&gt;, which is closest to the calculated result.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Unit of Energy:&lt;/strong&gt; Heat energy is expressed in &lt;strong&gt;Joules (J)&lt;/strong&gt;, the standard SI unit for energy.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Electric Power and Resistance:&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Electric power is directly proportional to the square of the voltage and inversely proportional to the resistance.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Higher resistance leads to lower power consumption for the same voltage.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Joule&amp;#39;s Law of Heating:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Joule&amp;rsquo;s law states that the heat produced in a conductor is proportional to the square of the current, resistance, and time.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Formula: &lt;strong&gt;H = I&amp;sup2; &amp;times; R &amp;times; t&lt;/strong&gt;, where &lt;strong&gt;I&lt;/strong&gt; is the current.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Applications of Electric Heaters:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Used in homes for water heating, space heating, and cooking.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Industrial applications include metal melting, drying, and chemical processes.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Energy Conversion in Heaters:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Electric heaters convert electrical energy into heat energy through resistance.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The efficiency of heaters depends on the material and design of the resistance element.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/important-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Important Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;SI Units:&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Energy: Joules (J)&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Power: Watts (W)&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Resistance: Ohms (&amp;Omega;)&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Time: Seconds (s)&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Practical Insights:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Always ensure proper voltage and resistance matching to prevent overheating or inefficiency.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Electric heaters should be used with safety measures to avoid accidents due to excessive heating or electrical faults.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

questions.statement:
The increase in which of the following factor(s) will increase the resistance of a conductor?&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
(i) Temperature of the conductor&lt;br /&gt;
(ii) Length of the conductor&lt;br /&gt;
(iii) Area of cross-section of the conductor

questions.explanation:
&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Both (i) and (ii)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;u style=&quot;font-size: 21px; font-weight: bolder; font-family: var(--bs-body-font-family); text-align: var(--bs-body-text-align);&quot;&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Temperature of the conductor (i):&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;An increase in the &lt;strong&gt;temperature&lt;/strong&gt; of a conductor causes an increase in its &lt;strong&gt;resistance&lt;/strong&gt;. This is because higher temperature results in an increased vibration of atoms, which in turn obstructs the flow of free electrons. &lt;em&gt;Hence, this statement is correct.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Length of the conductor (ii):&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Resistance is directly proportional to the &lt;strong&gt;length&lt;/strong&gt; of the conductor. A longer conductor has more material for the electrons to travel through, leading to increased resistance. &lt;em&gt;Hence, this statement is correct.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Area of cross-section of the conductor (iii):&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Resistance is inversely proportional to the &lt;strong&gt;area of cross-section&lt;/strong&gt; of a conductor. If the area increases, resistance decreases as more pathways are available for the electrons to flow. &lt;em&gt;Hence, this statement is incorrect.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Conclusion:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Only the &lt;strong&gt;temperature&lt;/strong&gt; and &lt;strong&gt;length&lt;/strong&gt; of the conductor increase the resistance, making option &amp;quot;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Both (i) and (ii)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&amp;quot; the correct answer.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Resistance and its Factors:&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The &lt;strong&gt;resistance&lt;/strong&gt; of a conductor determines how much it opposes the flow of electric current.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It is mathematically given by the formula: &lt;strong&gt;R = &amp;rho; &amp;times; (L/A)&lt;/strong&gt;, where:
		&lt;ul&gt;
			&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;R:&lt;/strong&gt; Resistance&lt;/li&gt;
			&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&amp;rho;:&lt;/strong&gt; Resistivity (depends on the material)&lt;/li&gt;
			&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;L:&lt;/strong&gt; Length of the conductor&lt;/li&gt;
			&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;A:&lt;/strong&gt; Area of cross-section of the conductor&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;/ul&gt;
		&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Effect of Temperature on Resistance:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;For most conductors, resistance increases with an increase in &lt;strong&gt;temperature&lt;/strong&gt;. This is due to enhanced atomic vibrations, which scatter the electrons.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;For semiconductors and insulators, resistance decreases with an increase in temperature.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Effect of Length on Resistance:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Resistance is directly proportional to the &lt;strong&gt;length&lt;/strong&gt; of the conductor. Thus, doubling the length of a conductor doubles its resistance.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Effect of Cross-sectional Area on Resistance:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Resistance is inversely proportional to the &lt;strong&gt;cross-sectional area&lt;/strong&gt;. For example, increasing the area by two times reduces the resistance to half.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Real-world Applications:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Understanding resistance is crucial for designing electrical components like resistors, wires, and circuits.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Materials with low resistance, such as copper and aluminum, are widely used in electrical wiring.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/important-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Important Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Resistivity:&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Resistivity is a material-specific property that quantifies how strongly a material opposes the flow of electric current.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It is denoted by &lt;strong&gt;&amp;rho;&lt;/strong&gt; and measured in &lt;strong&gt;ohm-meters (&amp;Omega;&amp;middot;m)&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Conductors vs. Insulators:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Conductors:&lt;/strong&gt; Materials with low resistivity (e.g., copper, aluminum).&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Insulators:&lt;/strong&gt; Materials with high resistivity (e.g., rubber, glass).&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Temperature Coefficient of Resistance:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;This term describes how the resistance of a material changes with temperature. It is positive for conductors and negative for semiconductors.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Applications in Electronics:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Resistors, thermostats, and temperature sensors are designed based on the principles of resistance.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
